title.rendered: South Africa vs Sri Lanka, Women’s T20 World Cup 2023: Fantasy Team, Probable Playing XI, Pitch Report, and Fantasy Tips for the Match

content.rendered:
We have opted for a fantasy cricket team based on the recent performances, overall impact, and credit points.

Probable Playing XIs for South Africa & Sri Lanka

South Africa: Tazmin Brits (c), Laura Wolvaardt, Chloe Tryon, Sune Luus, Delmi Tucker/Sinalo Jafta (wk), Marizanne Kapp, Nadine de Klerk, Masabata Klaas, Ayabonga Khaka, Nonkululeko Mlaba, Shabnim Ismail

Sri Lanka: Chamari Athapaththu (c), Anushka Sanjeewani (wk), Nilakshi de Silva, Kavisha Dilhari, Vishmi Gunaratne, Inoka Ranaweera, Oshadi Ranasinghe, Ama Kanchana, Harshitha Madavi, Sugandika Kumari, Achini Kulasuriya

Venue: Newlands, Cape Town

Pitch Report for South Africa vs Sri Lanka

(Based on the last three games)

1st innings average score: 125

2nd innings average score: 119

Wickets per innings: 6

Type: Balanced

Wins

Batting 1st: 67%

Batting 2nd: 33%

Also Read:

India vs Pakistan, Women’s T20 World Cup 2023 Fantasy Tips

Australia vs New Zealand, Women’s T20 World Cup 2023 Fantasy Tips

West Indies vs England, Women’s T20 World Cup, 2023 Fantasy Tips

Fantasy Tips of The Day

Marizanne Kapp and Shabnim Ismail are the leading wicket-takers for South Africa against Sri Lanka. While Kapp has taken 16 wickets in 12 games, Ismail has picked 12 wickets in 13 outings.

Sri Lanka will rely on their most experienced batter Chamari Athapaththu for a strong foundation at the top. Against South Africa, she has added 264 runs including the highest score of 52.

In her last seven games, Inoka Ranaweera has bagged as many as 13 wickets. Against South Africa, she has taken 8 wickets including three two-fors.

Besides averaging 26 with the bat at home, Sune Luus has hunted down 8 wickets against Sri Lanka including the best figures of 5 for 14.

When these teams last met, Nadine de Klerk (3 for 7) and Masabata Klaas (2 for 7) were the captain and vice-captain of the Ultimate Team respectively.

In the last three games at Newlands, spinners accounted for 36% of the wickets.
